segments.text: Something I think both you and I agree, that failed to capture the essence of Texas and the Southwest and the attitudes of people like yourself.
Who knew it, who went out, who fought for it, who struggled through it, who have that inner identity with it.
And yet you were called a country bumpkin.
Even my ex-husband was put down, right?
We saw something that was such an atrocity to really the preservation of history.
When you grow up in a town, and you see things, and you live in a house, and you know it, and then somebody come along and tell you, oh no, this is right.
that lived across the Mason-Vixon line and had probably never been in Johnson City.
And then they come in here and tell you what is what.
That's a bunch for the birds.
You do not go in and transform a community into what you fascinate it to be, you know, what your fascination might be that it is.
You don't set your birthright either.
No, which is something that the National Park did try to do to you.
I'm glad they're out of the picture now and that we're into something that's actually preserving history.
Is it about time to eat?
I've got to get this dinner going.
I don't care how big it is.
The deer ate the end of this off.
I've never had one like that.
Any time that I serve you something you can't eat, well, you just let me know, will you?
I have never turned down anything yet, Ava.
You know what you do with that, or I do with it rather, I take it and I put this Italian dressing on it.
I left that outside for a long time.
The seed's getting a little bit large.
Did you have a garden this year, Ava?
I started, but then I got hurt and I didn't get to finish it.
Now, I know that you're going to say, Miss Eve, I just can't believe this, but everybody has to fix his own salad.
But you take a raw squash, like I'm going to slice right here, and you put a little light salt on it and a little accent, and you use that salad dressing in there.
And you'll say, well, I just don't know.
I never had anything like this.
I don't know whether I even want to taste it or not.
But you'll find out that it doesn't taste like squash.
That's not very good for you, but.
How do you fry your squash?
I'll see if that's something I know how to do.
And sprinkle them with meal, and then fry them and leave them there.
I don't think I've had them that way.
Well, the buttermilk holds the... Of course, you know, in old times, you made use of what you had.
And you didn't disturb the cream on your milk.
And you churned every other day.
And that's why you'd always get buttermilk.
Yeah, you've come a long way in the kitchen from when you first began to grow up and eat out there on the ranch.
You'll have to tell me a little more about that.
You know, quite a difference in the management of a kitchen that you cook on a fireplace than one that you have a push-button kitchen.
Well, I don't exactly have a push-button kitchen, but I do have some conveniences far from the fireplace.
Now, you see all of these tomato peelings, squash bits, cucumber bits.
No, they wouldn't go in the disposal unit.
They'd go in a little can that would have a lid on it, which was a molasses bucket, usually.
They sat on a workbench or a work table, which would be much like this table right here.
And you would turn around, grab all that stuff up and put it in there.
Then you had a garbage bucket on the outside of the house that you put this stuff in and took and fed to the hogs.
You recycled it, more or less.
I think I lived the most wonderful days that Texas will ever see.
I think that, of course, that's my prerogative to believe that, but am I right?
But you take how many, well, there's just not too many people living today that can call back the time that Pancho Villa invaded Texas.
And remember how we were stirred up about it and what it really meant.
Then we come along to World War I, then World War II, then the Korean, then the Vietnamese.
And sit on my grandpappy's lap, and curl that long white beard, and hear him tell the stories of the Civil War.
You've known all of America's wars through.
I'm telling you, to me, that is a wonderful time to live.
And when my granddaddy Pepe was buried, there were six Confederate soldiers at his funeral.
I can't remember all of the song, but I can remember part of it.
I'll lay away a suit of gray to wear till the Union blew.
And to me, that was touching.
That's just my way of life.
I think of those things as.
Because I only knew one of my grandfathers too.
You've been fortunate to know many of them.
Yeah, he likes good food too.
You can put one over there on the bar.
OK. Or no, let's eat on the table.
These are not very good, but they'll answer the purpose today.
Here, I'll get that while you get the telephone.
My daddy was president of the old Trail Drivers of Texas for years.
And I believe the last year that he served as Trail Driver of Texas,
I have a picture that hangs on my wall of the last five original trail drivers in Texas.
And that's where I found out about the Copes, the Browns, the Lovings, and all of them, was through the old trail drivers and their organization that met in San Antonio at the Gunner Hotel.
And I used to go down there with my daddy to meetings.
And having driven cattle from San Antonio to Johnson City when I wasn't but 10 years old, I know what cattle driving is back in those days.
Now let me tell you, that was something.
And don't think it isn't, man.
advertising a trail ride to go do something.
It was no fun to me.
Well, they don't do it like we had to do it.
It was no fancy salon to bring your cattle through.
And I'm telling you, that was something else driving those things.
My daddy bought a bunch of Mexico steers.
You picked him up in San Antonio?
You know how we knew our stairs from anybody else's?
They bobtailed every one of those steers.
So that, you know, a steer will have a curl or a cow.
And whenever they lose that curl in their tail, they're too old.
Now, that's one of the markings my daddy told me as a little girl.
If you're not sure how old that cow is or whatnot, when that tail, that curl is out of that tail, ship them.
So when we took these steers off and ran them through the pen, we cut the tails off every one of them.
So that we'd know how to tell them if they were lost.
There at the sea blow, we had a storm come up.
And, well, they call it sea wall now, I think.
But anyway, we called it the sea blow.
Our cattle stampeded and ran in every direction.
But by call and by herding the next morning, we were able to get the biggest part of them back.
I've often heard of lightning jumping from horn to horn or hitting balls of fire.
I was like that little colored boy.
I was willing, but my feet just wouldn't stand still.
I got back to that wagon and I hurt.
You told me about that one time.
It made an impression on me that I'll never forget.
It was a storm came up.
And when the lightning had come out,
It would just jump like from horn to horn on those stairs.
I don't know what you'd call it because I never had the opportunity to see a bunch of stock in a herd that many.
And it was heat that drew it, I'm sure.
I think that's the static electricity that causes that.
I've heard of that, and you told me that story once before.
I never was scared of that in my life.
I wonder if I could have another one of those fattening biscuits over here.
Does that look like somebody's coming in here?
Well, how are you, Ms. Stewart?
Oh, I thought I'd come over here and welcome you to this street.
Can I have some beer with us?
I didn't know Lena called me and said you were going to have to go to Kitty Clyde and copy this down.
Well, I bet I can copy it and get it right.
Well, you don't have to come and just study.
Miss Stewart, this is my friend that used to work with the park here.
And I don't know your name.
I need a little ceiling up there.
No, but I'll sit down here and I'll show you this.
I didn't know you had something here.
I just come out of that garden of digging around.
Well, I've been in the house digging, trying to get things put away.
And I was late with dinner.
You look like you're doing real good around here with that.
You'd better have a roll with us.
This one, it just changes a little bit.
But this is the last one I have.
Yellow symbolizes constancy, teaches faithful obedience to the demands of honor and justice.
Ruth exemplified these virtues in humble station and sought the society of good and truth.
In token of appreciation of these virtues, I deposit the full tribute.
Now, that means it often changes it here.
And it's easier to say this than it is that.
But you aren't going to have a flyer to deposit saying Jerry told me.
Have you lost someone in the group?
That's a lot easier to say.
Yeah, it's a lot easier than this other.
Well, I'll just get my pencil right now and put this down.
Just take this and then just make that change and write the change down.
Because that's a lot easier for me.
Do you have a garden this year?
It's a pretty big one, but some of it's already withered.
Oh, yeah, it's in the forest.
They took care of it in the forest.
I eat a lot of squash raw.
I just introduced her to raw squash today.
I don't think she'd ever taste it.
I eat it raw and I eat it cooked.
Now this is the one we use?
I didn't know you were having dinner, Laura.
I thought you may be going to leave just in a little while the kitty cries.
So I just went on over here.
Yeah, but I was going to go over there and copy.
We kept her talking, so we got around to eating light.
Why don't I leave the books for you and let you cop it, and then I'll come get it.
Well, you might want to study it.
I've had three days to burn it.
Well, I didn't know it until last night.
Well, she called me about, she called everybody about three days ago.
Well, she sure didn't call me.
I've never been considered a member of that Eastern Star since I've been in there.
I stayed two weeks in that hospital.
And two days before I was to leave, they sent me some flowers.
But I guess she was in a hurry because she said she had to take her daughter home.
I think her daughter's been in the hospital or sick or something.
Well, Kitty Clyde didn't even tell me.
Well, she said she, I believe she called me the day before yesterday that she had to go.
Yeah, and she didn't think she'd get back.
